Portrait of Jacob Weston, an academic in his mid-twenties who has found himself in a precarious circumstance unrivaled by any other: trapped within an endless expanse of constricting passages and caliginous books packed tighter together than an introductory course on English morphology. But while he is isolated, he is far from alone; he is accompanied by Rosanne Walker, fellow student, female, with a penchant for reading between lines and thumbing through pages long forgotten by the mainstream.

At the present moment Jacob is preoccupied with determining how he materialized in this nightmarish realm. But he will come to find that the twisting halls and labyrinthine constructs are merely a symptom of a deeper, more entrenched malevolence that rests within the hearts of not just //man//, but //woman// too. This is no dissertation of depravity; rather, we will soon learn that while the monsters are most often men, heaven has no rage like love to hatred turned.

A consilient, agnostic preponderance of the highest order; an institutionalized incomprehensibility of incredulity, only ever listed amongst the abstracts of the Boundryless Confines.

