Death is no humerus subject. For the common man, death is ineffible, uncontainable, unstoppable, and he simply has no stomach for even a passing thought on the matter. It pervades every aspect of life in as much as it serves as its end; a bone-chilling conclusion to the glowing warmth of the thin slice of time we have on this Earth.

And yet, tibia husk of a man while still breathing because of this inevitable conclusion is a marrow perspective. For when we eventually fracture from this mortal coil and are cast into the next realm beyond, we will come to find that death does not, in fact, do us part. Truly a talus old as time: find it filed under "P" for "Phalangies", in the shadowy Sheol of the Boundryless Confines.

