A corpse is a type of shipwreck. Its former passengers, the cells and bacteria — now left to their own devices — blossom outwards. And as they spread, the body decays. Soon there is nothing left of the former host besides bones, memories, and microscopic refugees.

If a corpse is a shipwreck, then a person is a ship, carrying a tight crew: neuronic command centers and hemoglobin goblins, gut bacteria prisoners and B-Cell soldiers, all working together towards one common goal, though their means may differ: stay alive. Each individual has its role to play in the vast, complex machinery. And through this mutual cooperation, a equilibrium of membrane and mitosis, they manage to keep themselves afloat for another day.

This ship, in particular, is the //SS Bog Chaser//. And between the flowing blood vessels and the winding lymph nodes, two individuals find love amidst a growing, ever-looming threat, one that seems to have infiltrated the very fabric of the ship's defense systems. Keep your eyes on the microscope, or whatever other AID you may have, for this is not regular check up. This... is the Boundryless Confines.

